s looking pale and ghoulish. As Clayson shows, artists’ representations of these new colors and shapes reveal turn-of-the-century concerns about modernization as electric lighting came to represent the harsh glare of rapidly accelerating social change. At the same time, in part thanks to American artists visiting the city, these works of art also produced our enduring romantic view of Parisian glamour and its Belle Époque.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArt, Moderny19th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aArt, Moderny19th century. 0aArt, Modern-19th century. 0aLighting, Architectural and decorative, in art. 0aParis (France)-In art. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aImpressionism.  aParis.  acity lighting.  aelectric light.  agaslight.  aillumination.  aluminosity.  amodernism.  amodernity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226594057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226594057/original  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles